uch as Greta Garbo, who was worshipped for the masklike perfection of her face. Engaging, provocative, and filled with arresting and at times disturbing illustrations, Flags and Faces offers striking new insights into American art and visual culture from 1915 to 1930.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArt, Americany20th century. 0aPopular culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSymbolismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVisual communicationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vArt and the war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zUnited StatesxIn art. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zUnited StatesxPropaganda. 4aArt & Politics. 4aArt. 7aART / Art & Politics.2bisacsh1 aLubin, David M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028363340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035586640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520355866423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520355866/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles